  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, US)\n- First international anti-money laundering guidelines\n- Initial focus on reporting large cash transactions\n\n2. 1980s-1990s\n- FATF (Financial Action Task Force) established in 1989\n- More comprehensive international regulations\n- Increased emphasis on financial institution reporting\n- Criminalization of money laundering\n\n3. Post-9/11 Era\n- Patriot Act (2001)\n- Enhanced international cooperation\n- Stricter regulations on terrorist financing\n- Expanded due diligence requirements\n\n4. Recent Developments\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n- Beneficial ownership transparency\n- Advanced risk assessment frameworks\n- Increased global information sharing\n- Stricter penalties for non-compliance\n\n5. Key Legislative Mechanisms\n- Mandatory customer identification\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Enhanced cross-border financial tracking\n- Regular compliance audits\n- International collaboration\n\n6. Emerging Trends\n- AI and machine learning in detection\n- Blockchain-based compliance systems\n- More comprehensive regulatory frameworks\n\nThe legislation continues to evolve, adapting to technological and financial innovations.",
